instruct: Welcome to the Job-Simulator Task!
In this experiment, you will listen to one short story.
During the story, we will ask you to take on the perspective of a type of job.
This perpsective will be:
In other words, you should try to listen to the story from the perspective of this job. This is called “job simulation.”
Before getting to the story, we will teach you 4 questions associated with the perspective to use when listening to the story.
We encourage you to keep these questions in mind while listening to the story and simulating the assigned perspective.
When presented with the sequence of questions in a few moments, try to remember it.
Press the space bar to begin learning the sequence of questions.

instructText: You will now be quizzed on the 4 questions.
In the quiz, press the number key corresponding to the number in front of the question that comes first.
And then, press the number key for the second question, and so on for all 4 questions.
If you select the wrong question in the sequence, you will see the sequence of questions again and retake the quiz until you have successfully ordered the questions.
Press the space bar to begin the quiz.

instruct: Great job learning the sequence of questions! We will now move onto the story.
The story you will listen to will be presented sentence by sentence, such that each sentence is heard individually.
After each sentence plays, your task will be to make a judgement about each sentence in order to advance to the next sentence.
Some people feel that the story has natural “parts.” We want you to make a judgement about when you think the story has transitioned from one “part” to another.
Press “9” if you think the sentence you are reading has begun a new “part” of the story.
For example, you should press “9” at the beginning of a story and when you think a different “part” in the story is beginning.
Press “1” if you think the sentence is in the same “part” as the sentence before.
There are no “right” answers. We want to see what you think these parts are.
When you make the decision that each sentence is beginning a new part of the story or not by pressing "9" or "1", you will advance to the next sentence.
You will not be able to make the judgment until after the sentence has played fully.
You will not be able to go back to previous sentences or change the judgement you made about a previous sentence.
Press the space bar to get the perspective and quiz one final time.
In the final part of the experiment, please answer 8 questions about the story.
We did not tell you to think of all or some of these questions during the story, but please do your best to answer them.
Answer as much as you remember, and be specific and concrete in your answers. It is best to try to be as faithful as possible to what the story actually said.
When you have finished typing your answer, hit ‘return’ or ‘enter’ to submit your answer and move onto the next question.
Great job! There will be one more part of the experiment on a different site where you will first enter your Prolific_ID again and then answer various demographic questions and experiment questions.
Do not click out of this window- you will be redirected to the second part of the experiment once the first part ends.
You must complete the next part of the experiment to receive credit for participating.
